  "texts": [
    "We begin by estimating the latter asH(h ∞ |h eq)(t) = ∫ I h ∞ (w) log h ∞ (w) h eq (t, w) dw = log C ∞ C(t) ∫ I h ∞ (w)dw =1 +(b ∞ 1 -b 1 (t)) ∫ I log(1 -w)h ∞ (w)dw + (b ∞ 2 -b 2 (t)) ∫ I log(1 + w)h ∞ (w)dw ≤ C ∞ -C(t) C(t) + η ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h ∞ ∥ L q (I) e -τ t,(59)applying the bounds log x ≤ x -1 for any x > 0, b ∞ i -b i (t) ≤ λp(ωp+ε) 2 σ 2 p +σ 2 ℓ |m w (t) -µ ℓ | for i = 1,C ∞ -C(t) = C ∞ C(t)(B(b 1 (t), b 2 (t)) -B(b ∞ 1, b ∞ 2)) = C ∞ C(t) 2 ∫ I ((1 -w) -1+b 1 (t) -(1 -w) -1+b ∞ 1) ((1 + w) -1+b 2 (t) + (1 + w) -1+b ∞ 2) dw + C ∞ C(t) 2 ∫ I ((1 -w) -1+b 1 (t) + (1 -w) -1+b ∞ 1) ((1 + w) -1+b 2 (t) -(1 + w) -1+b ∞ 2) dw = C ∞ C(t) 2 ∫ I (1 -w) -1+b ∞ 1 ((1 -w) b 1 (t)-b ∞ 1 -1) ((1 + w) -1+b 2 (t) + (1 + w) -1+b ∞ 2) dw + C ∞ C(t) 2 ∫ I ((1 -w) -1+b 1 (t) + (1 -w) -1+b ∞ 1) (1 + w) -1+b ∞ 2 ((1 + w) b 2 (t)-b ∞ 2 -1) dw,(60)and we expect the differences (1 -w) b 1 (t)-b ∞ 1 -1 and (1 + w) b 2 (t)-b ∞ 2 -1 to vanish exponentially in the limit t → +∞.",
    "We prove this fact for the first difference (the second will follow similarly), by rewriting it as(1 -w) b 1 (t)-b ∞ 1 -1 = (b 1 (t) -b ∞ 1) log(1 -w) ∫ 1 0 (1 -w) s(b 1 (t)-b ∞ 1) ds = ξe -τ t log(1 -w) ∫ 1 0 (1 -w) sξe -τ t ds,where ξ = -λp(ωp+ε) 2 σ 2 p +σ 2 ℓ (m in w -µ ℓ) and τ > 0 are two constants, and the sign of ξ is determined by that of the initial condition m in w -µ ℓ.",
    "The delicate case occurs when ξ < 0, since one needs to control an integral term of the form ∫ I ∫ 1 0 (1 -w) -s|ξ|e -τ t dsdw, which could be unbounded depending on the parameters of the problem (notice that the integration in s does not cause any additional problem).",
    "However, the presence of the exponential decay e -τ t ensures that this issue is prevented for t large enough.",
    "In particular, for any given q ′ > 1 one can find a threshold time T > 0 such that the function g(w) = log(1 -w)(1 -w) sξe -τ t belongs to L q ′ (I) for any s ∈ [0, 1] and t ≥ T. Let us recall that there exists q > 1 such that h eq ∈ L ∞ (R +, L q (I)) and h ∞ ∈ L q (I)."
  ]
